[2] ECDC weekly report
Date: Fri 30 Mar 2012
Source: European Centre For Disease Control, Weekly Surveillance Report [edited]
http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/120330_SUR_Weekly_Influenza_Surveillance_Overview.pdf


Main surveillance developments in week 12/2012 (19-25 Mar 2012)
---------------------------------------------------------------
The 2011/12 influenza season started late and has been without any clear geographic progression. The following points are noteworthy this week:

- Decreasing trends were reported by 21 countries, 14 of which have reported such trends for at least 2 consecutive weeks while only Lithuania, Poland and Slovakia reported increasing trends.

- Of 940 sentinel specimens tested, 42.9 percent were positive for influenza virus. This proportion was unchanged compared to week 11 after declining steadily from a peak of 58 percent in week 8. Of the positive sentinel specimens, 75.2 percent were type A and 24.8 percent type B. The proportion of influenza B viruses has continued to increase.

- There has been a degree of heterogeneity in the antigenicity of the A(H3) viruses this season and an imperfect fit with the A(H3) component in the seasonal vaccine.

- Since week 40/2011, a total of 1513 SARI cases, including 79 fatalities, have been reported by seven countries. Of these cases, most were influenza-related.

- No resistance to neuraminidase inhibitors (oseltamivir and zanamivir) has been reported so far this season.

The decrease in the proportion of influenza-positive sentinel specimens and the growing number of countries reporting continuously decreasing trends in ILI/ARI notifications indicate that the epidemic has passed its peak in most European countries. As often observed late in the season, the proportion of type B virus influenza detections has been increasing over the past 6 weeks.

Sentinel surveillance of influenza-like illness (ILI)/ acute respiratory infection (ARI): Medium or low intensity was indicated by all 28 reporting countries. For more detailed information, go to: http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/120330_SUR_Weekly_Influenza_Surveillance_Overview.pdf.

Virological surveillance: Of 403 sentinel specimens testing positive for influenza virus, 303 (75.2 percent) were type A and 100 (24.8 percent) type B. For more detailed information, go to: http://ecdc.europa.eu/en/publications/Publications/120330_SUR_Weekly_Influenza_Surveillance_Overview.pdf.

